</ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Loyalists_in_literature">Loyalists in literature</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Loyalist_(American_Revolution)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Loyalists in literature"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Category:Novels_set_during_the_American_Revolutionary_War" title="Category:Novels set during the American Revolutionary War">Category:Novels set during the American Revolutionary War</a></div>
<ul><li><i>The Adventures of Jonathan Corncob, Loyal American Refugee</i> (1787) by Jonathan Corncob. According to Maya Jasanoff, "traveling to London to file a claim served as the opening gambit" for this "<a href="/wiki/Picaresque_novel" title="Picaresque novel">picaresque novel</a> about the American Revolution".<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>"<a href="/wiki/Rip_Van_Winkle" title="Rip Van Winkle">Rip Van Winkle</a>" (1819), short story by <a href="/wiki/Washington_Irving" title="Washington Irving">Washington Irving</a><sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><i><a href="/wiki/The_Spy_(Cooper_novel)" title="The Spy (Cooper novel)">The Spy: a Tale of the Neutral Ground</a></i> (1821), novel by <a href="/wiki/James_Fenimore_Cooper" title="James Fenimore Cooper">James Fenimore Cooper</a></li>
<li><i>Oliver Wiswell</i> (1940), a novel by <a href="/wiki/Kenneth_Roberts_(author)" title="Kenneth Roberts (author)">Kenneth Roberts</a></li>
<li><cite id="CITEREFDownieDownie1971" class="citation book cs1"><a href="/wiki/Mary_Alice_Downie" title="Mary Alice Downie">Downie, Mary Alice</a>; Downie, John (1971). <i>Honor Bound</i>. illus. Joan Huffman. Toronto: <a href="/wiki/Oxford_University_Press" title="Oxford University Press">Oxford University Press</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-19-540192-1" title="Special:BookSources/0-19-540192-1"><bdi>0-19-540192-1</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Honor+Bound&amp;rft.place=Toronto&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1971&amp;rft.isbn=0-19-540192-1&amp;rft.aulast=Downie&amp;rft.aufirst=Mary+Alice&amp;rft.au=Downie%2C+John&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALoyalist+%28American+Revolution%29" class="Z3988"></span></li>
<li><i><a href="/wiki/The_Book_of_Negroes_(novel)" title="The Book of Negroes (novel)">The Book of Negroes</a></i> (2007) by <a href="/wiki/Lawrence_Hill" title="Lawrence Hill">Lawrence Hill</a></li>
<li><i><a href="/wiki/The_Fort_(novel)" title="The Fort (novel)">The Fort</a></i> (2010), novel by <a href="/wiki/Bernard_Cornwell" title="Bernard Cornwell">Bernard Cornwell</a></li>
<li><cite id="CITEREFLong_Stanley2019" class="citation book cs1">Long Stanley, Wendy (2019). <i>The Power to Deny: A Woman of the Revolution Novel</i>. Carmenta Publishing. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-951747-00-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-951747-00-8"><bdi>978-1-951747-00-8</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Power+to+Deny%3A+A+Woman+of+the+Revolution+Novel&amp;rft.pub=Carmenta+Publishing&amp;rft.date=2019&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-951747-00-8&amp;rft.aulast=Long+Stanley&amp;rft.aufirst=Wendy&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALoyalist+%28American+Revolution%29" class="Z3988"></span> Well received historical fiction account of the life of Elizabeth Graeme Fergusson</li></ul>
